	There is a big distinction to be made between being IP connected and
	non-IP connected.  DNS access requires IP connectivity, end-to-end.  
Not necessarily: network A may have IP connection that doesn't
go beyond some external network B; if [a host on] network B has
Internet access, network A has access to the DNS without there
being full end-to-end IP connectivity.

	Fully-connected == IP Connected, and implies DNS access via IP.
	
	Not-Fully-Connected == UUCP, or MMDF/phnoenet, or BITNET or &lt;?&gt;
	connected, and implies no DNS access.  

The case I gave above I would call semi-connected.


	Piet

